Log Regression¶

In [23]:
import statsmodels.api as sm

# Keep only positive values to avoid log issues
df_reg = df1[(df1['base_passenger_fare'] > 0) &
            (df1['trip_miles'] > 0) &
            (df1['trip_time'] > 0)].copy()


# Take natural logs
df_reg['log_fare']  = np.log(df_reg['base_passenger_fare'])
df_reg['log_miles'] = np.log(df_reg['trip_miles'])
df_reg['log_time']  = np.log(df_reg['trip_time'])

# --- 2. Run log-log regression ---
X = df_reg[['log_miles', 'log_time']]
X = sm.add_constant(X)  # adds intercept
y = df_reg['log_fare']

model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()
print(model.summary())

# --- 3. Interpret ---
# Coefficients are elasticities
elasticity_miles = model.params['log_miles']
elasticity_time  = model.params['log_time']

print(f"Elasticity of fare w.r.t miles: {elasticity_miles:.3f}")
print(f"Elasticity of fare w.r.t time: {elasticity_time:.3f}")

Elasticity of fare w.r.t time: 0.379

Inference: So, in the aggregate, time is a slightly stronger predictor of fare than distance (opposite of what we saw in the linear regression).

Why?

Because short congested trips (low miles, high time) are common in NYC, which inflates the role of time when working in percentage terms.

Elasticities normalize by scale, so the model highlights relative sensitivity rather than raw dollar impact.

# Define Distance Bins, add bins to df ---
bins = [0, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 600]   # adjust as needed
labels = ["0-2 mi", "2-5 mi", "5-10 mi", "10-20 mi", "20-50 mi", "50+ mi"]
df1_reg['distance_bin'] = pd.cut(df1_reg['trip_miles'], bins=bins, labels=labels, right=False)

StatementMeta(, 60c81d03-0760-42a9-a87c-d07c9e401f20, 27, Finished, Available, Finished)
In [27]:
# Run Log-Log Regression in Each Bin ---
elasticities = []

for bin_label in labels:
    subset = df1_reg[df1_reg['distance_bin'] == bin_label]
    if len(subset) < 1000:  # skip bins with very few trips
        continue
    
    # log-transform safely (no 0s)
    subset['log_fare']  = np.log(subset['base_passenger_fare'])
    subset['log_miles'] = np.log(subset['trip_miles'])
    subset['log_time']  = np.log(subset['trip_time'])
    
    X = sm.add_constant(subset[['log_miles', 'log_time']])
    y = subset['log_fare']
    model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()
    
    elasticity_miles = model.params['log_miles']
    elasticity_time  = model.params['log_time']
    
    elasticities.append({
        'bin': bin_label,
        'elasticity_miles': elasticity_miles,
        'elasticity_time': elasticity_time
    })

Hypothesis Testing¶

Formal Hypotheses

1. Overall elasticities differ¶

𝐻0: 𝛽miles = 𝛽time

𝐻1 : 𝛽miles ≠ 𝛽time

In [32]:
# Wald test: are log_miles and log_time coefficients equal?
wald_test = model.wald_test("log_miles = log_time")
print(wald_test)

StatementMeta(, 60c81d03-0760-42a9-a87c-d07c9e401f20, 33, Finished, Available, Finished)
<F test: F=array([[608.09820298]]), p=1.2587467156720366e-132, df_denom=2.42e+04, df_num=1>

Inference:

F = 608.10 p = 1.26e-132 df_num = 1 df_denom ≈ 24,200 Null hypothesis (H₀): β_miles = β_time

Alternative (H₁): β_miles ≠ β_time

F-statistic = 608 → very large, meaning the coefficients are very different.

p-value ≈ 1e-132 → essentially 0, far below any conventional significance level (0.05, 0.01, 0.001).

✅ Conclusion: Reject H₀. The elasticity of fare with respect to miles is not equal to the elasticity with respect to time in this bin. One clearly dominates.

2. Elasticities differ by trip length (heterogeneity)¶

𝐻0 : 𝛽milesshort = 𝛽mileslong

𝐻1 : 𝛽milesshort ≠ 𝛽mileslong

3. Tipping point exists¶

𝐻0 : No distance range where miles elasticity > time elasticity.

𝐻1 : There exists a cut-off where miles elasticity overtakes time elasticity.

→ Test: fit interaction model

ln(Fare) = 𝛼 + 𝛽1 ln(Miles) + 𝛽2 ln(Time) + 𝛽3𝐼(Miles > 5) ⋅ ln(Miles) + 𝜖

If 𝛽3 is significant, it means the effect of miles changes above 5 miles.

Inferences:

Null hypothesis (H₀): The effect of miles on fare does not change above 5 miles.

Alternative (H₁): The effect of miles on fare changes above 5 miles.

✅ With p ≈ 0.0 (essentially < 0.001), you reject H₀. 👉 This means: the relationship between fare and distance is structurally different once trips are longer than 5 miles.

In [66]:
# Candidate cut-offs
cutoffs = [3, 5, 7, 10, 15, 20]

f_stats = []

for c in cutoffs:
    # Define dummy and interaction
    df1_test['long_dummy'] = (df1_test['trip_miles'] > c).astype(int)
    df1_test['log_miles_interact'] = df1_test['log_miles'] * df1_test['long_dummy']
    
    # Fit regression
    X = sm.add_constant(df1_test[['log_miles', 'log_time', 'log_miles_interact']])
    y = df1_test['log_fare']
    model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()
    
    # Wald test for interaction
    test_result = model.wald_test("log_miles_interact = 0")
    f_value = float(test_result.fvalue)   # extract F-statistic
    f_stats.append(f_value)

# Plot F-statistic by cutoff
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.plot(cutoffs, f_stats, marker='o')
plt.title("F-statistic of Structural Break vs. Distance Cut-off", fontsize=14, weight='bold')
plt.xlabel("Trip Distance Cut-off (miles)")
plt.ylabel("F-statistic")
plt.grid(True, linestyle="--", alpha=0.6)

# Highlight max
best_cutoff = cutoffs[np.argmax(f_stats)]
best_f = max(f_stats)
plt.axvline(best_cutoff, color="red", linestyle="--", alpha=0.7)
plt.text(best_cutoff+0.2, best_f*0.9, f"Best cut-off ~{best_cutoff} mi", color="red")

plt.show()
